    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The angle of the orbit, also known as the orbital inclination, plays a significant role in how close two planets appear to be in conjunction. Think of it like a goblin trying to sneak up on a giant, but the giant is standing on a slope. The goblin's approach angle affects how close it appears to be to the giant.\n\nIn the case of planetary conjunctions, the orbital inclination is the angle between the planes of the two planets' orbits around the Sun. When the inclination is close to 0°, the planets appear to be aligned almost perfectly, and their distances from each other are similar. However, when the inclination is greater, the planets appear to be at slightly different distances, even when they're in conjunction.\n\nFor example, if Jupiter and Mars have an inclination of about 1.3°, they'll appear to be about 1% closer to each other in conjunction than if they had an inclination of 0°. This might not seem like a lot, but it can make a noticeable difference in the apparent brightness and size of the planets in the sky.\n\nThe reason for this effect is that the inclination affects the apparent distance between the planets, which in turn affects their angular separation. The more inclined the",
